MDMA/Psychadelics multi-level meta analysis

Nicklas Hafiz

27 April, 2024

## - The library is already synchronized with the lockfile.

Introduction

The analysis follows the chapter Fitting Three-Level Meta-Analysis Models in R from the book Doing Meta-Analysis in R, Harrer et al. (2021).

We used R version 4.3.3 (R Core Team 2024a) and the following R packages: dmetar v. 0.1.0 (Harrer et al. 2019), extrafont v. 0.19 (Chang 2023), ggbrace v. 0.1.0 (Huber, n.d.), ggtext v. 0.1.2 (Wilke and Wiernik 2022), grid v. 4.3.3 (R Core Team 2024b), here v. 1.0.1 (Müller 2020), knitr v. 1.45 (Xie 2014, 2015, 2023), metafor v. 4.4.0 (Viechtbauer 2010), psych v. 2.3.12 (William Revelle 2023), renv v. 1.0.3 (Ushey and Wickham 2023), rmarkdown v. 2.25 (Xie, Allaire, and Grolemund 2018; Xie, Dervieux, and Riederer 2020; Allaire et al. 2023), rstatix v. 0.7.2 (Kassambara 2023), tidyverse v. 2.0.0 (Wickham et al. 2019).

Main analysis

Because some studies provide multiple values we use a three-level Meta-Analysis Model. The nested random effect gets assigned to the grouping variable “study”. This means we allow the random intercept to vary across different studys. To obtain the estimated effect sizes for our two drugType levels we removed the intercept, as described in the documentation of the metafor Package. Test statistics and confidence intervals for the fixed effects use a t-distribution. The test of moderators checks the assumption that \(\mu_{mdma} = \mu_{psych} = 0\), so we get a test for an overall effect of the variable drugType.

To compare both drugType levels we defined a contrast, testing if \(\mu_{mdma} - \mu_{psych} = 0\) (Wald-Type Test), see ?anova.rma.

\(I^2\)

How much heterogeneity is due to differences within studies (level 2), and how much due to between study-differences (level 3)? So are the effect sizes from the same study more similar than effect sizes from multiple studies?

Interpretation

  • Variance Components:
    • sigma^2.1 contains the level 3 between-cluster variance.
    • sigma^2.2 shows the variance within clusters (level 2).
  • Test of Moderators: Indicates differences between the subgroups mdma & psychadelics.
  • Model Results
    • estimate is our estimated pooled effect.
  • $I^2$:
    • \(I^2\) quantifies the amount of variation not attributable to sampling error. In three level models, it is split into a part attributable to true effect size differences within clusters (level 2) and between cluster variation (level 3). We have 2 \(I^2\) values per model quantifying the percentage of total variation associated with either level 2 or level 3.
